Getting_Started_with_CEAR

BuKyung Baik

2025-01-17

1. Introduction

CEAR (Conditional Enrichment Analysis for Regulation) is an R package designed for sophisticated gene set association analysis with a focus on regulatory relationships in disease contexts. It provides specialized tools for:

  • Analyzing enrichment between different types of regulatory elements
  • Integrating disease-specific expression patterns through DEGs
  • Visualizing complex regulatory networks
  • Statistical assessment of gene set associations

2. Installation

Installing CEAR: Conditional Enrichment Analysis for Regulation

System Requirements

Before installing CEAR, ensure your system meets the following requirements:

  1. R version 3.5.0 or higher
  2. GNU GMP (version 4.2.3 or higher)
  3. GNU MPFR (version 3.0.0 or higher)
  4. C++11 compiler

Installing GNU GMP and MPFR

The installation process varies depending on your operating system:

For Linux Users (Ubuntu/Debian):

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install libgmp-dev
sudo apt-get install libmpfr-dev

For macOS Users:

Using Homebrew:

brew install gmp
brew install mpfr

For Windows Users:

  1. Install Rtools from https://cran.r-project.org/bin/windows/Rtools/
  2. GMP and MPFR are included in Rtools40 and higher

Verifying System Requirements

You can verify the GMP installation in R using:

if (requireNamespace("gmp", quietly = TRUE)) {
    cat("GMP is properly installed\n")
} else {
    cat("GMP is not installed\n")
}

You can install CEAR directly from GitHub using the devtools package:

# Install devtools if not already installed
if (!requireNamespace("devtools", quietly = TRUE))
    install.packages("devtools")

# Install CEAR from GitHub
devtools::install_github("unistbig/CEAR")

3. Data Preparation

CEAR requires three main types of data for comprehensive analysis of regulatory relationships in disease contexts. Here well explore both the built-in datasets and how to prepare your own data.

3.1 Built-in Disease Expression Data

CEAR provides preprocessed differential expression data for various diseases through the get_genes_preset() function:

library(CEAR)
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'GGally':
##   method from   
##   +.gg   ggplot2
## Warning: replacing previous import 'magrittr::extract' by 'tidyr::extract' when
## loading 'CEAR'
# Available disease types include:
# - Cancer types from TCGA: "BRCA", "LUAD", "LIHC", "PRAD", "STAD", "GBM", 
#                          "HNSC", "LUSC", "BLCA", "COAD"
# - Other diseases: "NAFLD", "COVID-19", "Alzheimer"

# Example 1: Get upregulated DEGs for NAFLD
nafld_up_degs <- get_genes_preset(
  disease.type = "NAFLD",
  gene.type = "DEG",
  adj.p.cutoff = 0.1,    # Adjust p-value threshold
  logfc.cutoff = 1,      # Log fold change threshold
  fold_direction = "Up"  # Direction of regulation
)

# Example 2: Get downregulated DEGs for breast cancer
brca_down_degs <- get_genes_preset(
  disease.type = "BRCA",
  gene.type = "DEG",
  adj.p.cutoff = 0.05,
  logfc.cutoff = -1,
  fold_direction = "Down"
)

# Example 3: Get background genes for liver cancer
lihc_background <- get_genes_preset(
  disease.type = "LIHC",
  gene.type = "Background genes"
)

3.2 Built-in Known Disease Genes

CEAR incorporates disease-gene associations from multiple authoritative sources:

  • DisGeNET database: Gene-disease associations
  • Comparative Toxicogenomics Database (CTD): Curated disease-gene relationships
  • KEGG pathways: Disease-specific pathway genes

Access these known disease genes using:

# Get known disease genes for specific conditions
alzheimer_known <- get_genes_preset(
  disease.type = "Alzheimer",
  gene.type = "Known genes"
)

covid_known <- get_genes_preset(
  disease.type = "COVID-19",
  gene.type = "Known genes"
)

3.3 Built-in Gene Set Collections

CEAR includes several comprehensive gene set collections:

  1. Transcription Factor (TF) Target Sets
# DoRothEA database with different confidence levels
tf_all <- `Geneset_tf(dorothea)`                                     # All TF targets
tf_confident <- `Geneset_tf.confident(dorothea)`                     # High-confidence (A) targets
tf_activators <- `Geneset_tf.confident_activator(dorothea)`          # Activating TFs
tf_repressors <- `Geneset_tf.confident_repressor(dorothea)`          # Repressing TFs

# GTRD database
tf_gtrd <- `Geneset_tf.gtrd(msigdb)`
  1. miRNA Target Sets
# TargetScan predictions
mirna_family <- `Geneset_mir_family(targetscan)`

# miRDB predictions
mirna_targets <-`Geneset_c3.mirdb(msigdb)`
  1. Pathway Gene Sets
# Different pathway databases
reactome <- `Geneset_reactome(msigdb)`           # Reactome pathways
wikipathways <- `Geneset_wikipathways(msigdb)`   # WikiPathways
go_bp <- `Geneset_go_bp(msigdb)`                 # GO Biological Process terms

3.4 Preparing Custom Data

While CEAR provides extensive built-in data, you can also use your own custom data. Heres how to format your data for CEAR analysis:

  1. Custom Gene Sets

Gene sets should be organized as named lists where each element contains a character vector of gene symbols:

# Custom TF target sets
custom_tf_sets <- list(
  "TF1" = c("BRCA1", "TP53", "PTEN", "ATM"),
  "TF2" = c("MYC", "CCND1", "CDK4", "E2F1")
)

# Custom pathway sets
custom_pathway_sets <- list(
  "DNA_Repair" = c("BRCA1", "BRCA2", "RAD51", "PARP1"),
  "Cell_Cycle" = c("CCND1", "CDK4", "E2F1", "RB1")
)
  1. Custom DEG List

Differentially expressed genes should be provided as a character vector:

custom_degs <- c("BRCA1", "MYC", "CCND1", "PARP1")
  1. Custom Background Gene Set

Define the universe of all possible genes for your analysis:

custom_background <- c("BRCA1", "TP53", "PTEN", "ATM", "MYC", "CCND1", 
                      "CDK4", "E2F1", "BRCA2", "RAD51", "PARP1", "RB1")
  1. Data Format Requirements

When preparing custom data, ensure:

  • All gene symbols are consistent across datasets
  • Gene symbols match the format of standard gene nomenclature (e.g., HGNC symbols)
  • Lists have unique names
  • Background gene set includes all genes that appear in your analysis
  • DEGs are a subset of your background genes
# Example of data validation
check_data <- function(gene_sets, degs, background) {
  # Check if all genes in sets are in background
  all_genes <- unique(unlist(gene_sets))
  in_background <- all_genes %in% background
  
  # Check if all DEGs are in background
  degs_in_background <- degs %in% background
  
  list(
    "all_genes_in_background" = all(in_background),
    "all_degs_in_background" = all(degs_in_background),
    "missing_genes" = all_genes[!in_background],
    "missing_degs" = degs[!degs_in_background]
  )
}

4. Basic Analysis

This section demonstrates the basic workflow of CEAR using a step-by-step example. Well analyze the relationship between transcription factors, pathways, and differentially expressed genes in NAFLD (Non-alcoholic Fatty Liver Disease).

4.1 Setting Up the Analysis

First, lets prepare our data:

library(CEAR)

# Get NAFLD genes(DEGs, known disease genes and background genes)
nafld_down_degs <- get_genes_preset(
  disease.type = "NAFLD",
  gene.type = "DEG",
  adj.p.cutoff = 0.1,
  logfc.cutoff = 0,
  fold_direction = "Down"
)

nafld_up_degs <- get_genes_preset(
  disease.type = "NAFLD",
  gene.type = "DEG",
  adj.p.cutoff = 0.1,
  logfc.cutoff = 0,
  fold_direction = "Up"
)

nafld_background <- get_genes_preset(
  disease.type = "NAFLD",
  gene.type = "Background genes"
)

nafld_known <- get_genes_preset(
  disease.type = "NAFLD",
  gene.type = "Known genes"
)

# Prepare gene sets
tf_sets <- `Geneset_tf.confident_activator(dorothea)`             # High-confidence activating TFs
pathway_sets <- `Geneset_wikipathways(msigdb)`                    # WikiPathway gene sets

# Filter gene sets to include only background genes
tf_sets <- lapply(tf_sets, function(x) intersect(x, nafld_background))
pathway_sets <- lapply(pathway_sets, function(x) intersect(x, nafld_background))

# Remove small gene sets (less than 10 genes)
tf_sets <- tf_sets[sapply(tf_sets, length) >= 30]
pathway_sets <- pathway_sets[sapply(pathway_sets, length) >= 30]

4.2 Simple Overlap Analysis

Lets start with a basic analysis between TF targets and pathway genes:

# Calculate overlaps between TF targets and pathways
overlaps <- conditional_overlap_pvalue.elements(
  n1 = tf_sets$PPARA,           # Target genes of PPARA
  n2 = pathway_sets$`WP_FATTY_ACID_BETA_OXIDATION`,  # Fatty acid pathway genes
  deg = nafld_up_degs           # Upregulated genes in NAFLD
)

print(overlaps)
## [1] 0.0439025

4.3 Comprehensive Analysis

Now, lets perform a more comprehensive analysis across all TFs and pathways:

# Analyze all pairs of TFs and pathways
all_results <- overlap_pvalue_ALL.groups(
  n1 = pathway_sets,            # Pathway gene sets
  n2 = tf_sets,                 # TF target gene sets
  deg = nafld_up_degs,         # Upregulated genes
  background = nafld_background,# Background genes
  known_genes = nafld_known     # Known NAFLD genes
)

# View the first few results
head(all_results)

4.4 Filtering Significant Results

Filter the results to focus on significant associations:

significant_results <- select_significant_overlaps.groups(
  results = all_results,
  init.filter = c("overlap.gs.p", "overlap.gs_deg.p"),
  init.thr = 0.05,             # Initial p-value threshold
  final.filter = c("overlap.conditional.degs.q"),
  final.thr = 0.05,            # FDR threshold
  do.known.filter = TRUE       # Include known gene filter
)

# View filtered results

4.5 Result Interpretation

The key columns in our results include:

  • overlap.gs.p: P-value for general gene set overlap
  • overlap.gs_deg.p: P-value for overlap with DEGs
  • overlap.conditional.degs.p: Conditional probability considering DEG context
  • overlap.gsdeg_known.p: P-value for overlap with known disease genes

Lower p-values indicate stronger associations between the regulatory elements.

# Example of interpreting top results
top_results <- head(significant_results[order(significant_results$overlap.conditional.degs.q), ])
print(top_results[, c("n1", "n2", "overlap.conditional.degs.q")])

4.6 Output Formats

You can save your results in various formats:

# Save results to a file
write.table(significant_results, 
            file = "nafld_tf_pathway_analysis.txt", 
            sep = "\t", 
            row.names = FALSE)

# Create a summary of top associations
result_summary <- data.frame(
  Pathway = significant_results$n1,
  TF = significant_results$n2,
  Q_value = significant_results$overlap.conditional.degs.q
)

5. Network Visualization

CEAR provides powerful network visualization capabilities to help understand the relationships between regulatory elements. There are two main types of visualizations: single-layer and multi-layer networks.

5.1 Single-Layer Network Visualization

First, lets create a network showing relationships between TFs and pathways:

# Visualize TF-Pathway relationships
plot_network_single(
  result1 = significant_results,
  n1.type = "Pathway",
  n2.type = "TF",
  p.sort = "overlap.conditional.degs.p",  # Sort by conditional p-value
  de.direction = "up",                    # Color edges for upregulation
  using.n2DE = TRUE,                      # Filter for DE TFs
  n2de = nafld_up_degs[nafld_up_degs%in%names(tf_sets)],                  # DE TF list
  using.top = 10,                        # Show top 20 relationships
  filename.plot = "tf_pathway_network.pdf",
  filename.df = "tf_pathway_network.txt",
  width = 12,
  height = 8
)

5.2 Multi-Layer Network Visualization

Now, lets create a more complex network incorporating miRNAs as well:

# First, analyze miRNA-pathway relationships
mirna_sets <- `Geneset_mir_family(targetscan)`
mirna_sets <- lapply(mirna_sets, function(x) intersect(x, nafld_background))
mirna_sets <- mirna_sets[sapply(mirna_sets, length) >= 30]

mirna_results <- overlap_pvalue_ALL.groups(
  n1 = pathway_sets,
  n2 = mirna_sets,
  deg = nafld_down_degs,      # miRNAs often show inverse correlation
  background = nafld_background,
  known_genes = nafld_known
)

significant_mirna_results <- select_significant_overlaps.groups(
  results = mirna_results,
  init.thr = 0.05,
  final.thr = 0.05
)

# Create integrated network
plot_network_multi(
  result1 = significant_results,     # TF results
  result2 = significant_mirna_results, # miRNA results
  n1.type = "Pathway",
  n2.1.type = "TF",
  n2.2.type = "miRNA",
  de.direction1 = "up",              # TFs up-regulated
  de.direction2 = "down",            # miRNAs down-regulated
  using.n2.1DE = TRUE,
  n2.1de = nafld_up_degs[nafld_up_degs%in%names(tf_sets)],
  using.n2.2DE = F,
  using.top1 = 15,                   # Top 15 TF relationships
  using.top2 = 15,                   # Top 15 miRNA relationships
  filename.plot = "integrated_network.pdf",
  filename.df = "integrated_network.txt",
  width = 15,
  height = 10
)
